In Greek it ought to be *χώρᾰ-συ; but we have already seen¹ the regular substitutiones -σιν for -crv,² whence the type δραχμῇ-σι, χώρᾶ-σιν, which serves at once as a locative, dative, ablativo and instrumental in Homer and Herodotus, and which has been preserved in classical Greek only in the type Ἀθήνησι, Πλαταιᾶσιν, with a strictly locative function. The analogy of the termination -οισι of the 2nd declension caused the addition of an ι subscript, κεφαλῇσιν, a spelling which is almost invariable in manuscripts, but not in inscriptions. Another termination -αισι (Old Attio), more directly modelled on -οισι, seems to have only spread very slightly.
